Butler takes on IBF super-featherweight champion Zolani Tete in what will be the South African’s first defence.

Butler, 26, previously moved up to bantamweight to take on then world champion Stuart Hall, winning by split decision in Newcastle.

‘It’s going to be a magical night at the Echo Arena with my fans backing me all the way to a second world title,’ he said. 

‘It’s by no means going to be an easy night against Tete, who’s a very tough and experienced champion, but fighting for the world title in front of my fans at home means the world to me and that will give me the extra determination to win it.’

